Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in contrastive learning (CL) for long documents lies in the phenomenon of length-induced semantic drift—where increasing document length inadvertently amplifies intra-document similarity, distorting the learned representations and undermining semantic fidelity. While Paper 1 identifies this vulnerability and proposes a length-agnostic framework, it primarily treats length as noise to be normalized. However, structural cues within documents—such as sections, subsections, and paragraph hierarchies—are not merely organizational artifacts but carry intrinsic semantic signals that reflect how meaning is constructed incrementally across text. Papers 2 and 3 highlight that document structure is both learnable and beneficial, yet no existing work explicitly leverages hierarchical structure *as a dynamic scaffold* during contrastive training to actively counteract semantic drift. My intuition is that instead of viewing structure as auxiliary information or a post-hoc enhancement, we can integrate it into the contrastive objective itself—using structural boundaries to define meaningful semantic units for positive/negative sampling and aligning embeddings at multiple granularities. This transforms structure from passive metadata into an active regulator of semantic coherence. Unlike prior methods that either ignore structure (e.g., LA(SER)³) or use it only for downstream infusion, our idea embeds structural awareness directly into the contrastive learning mechanism, enabling models to resist semantic dilution by anchoring representations to their hierarchical context. This approach is fundamentally novel because it reframes document structure as a *semantic stabilizer*, dynamically guiding the alignment of embeddings in proportion to structural depth and functional role.

