  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called Latent Hierarchical Contrastive Learning (LHCL), which addresses length-induced semantic drift by jointly learning document representations and their underlying hierarchical structure in an end-to-end manner. Rather than relying on pre-parsed or externally annotated structures—as in HSA or SDHG—LHCL treats document hierarchy as a latent variable inferred during training through a differentiable, attention-guided tree induction mechanism. The model operates via two parallel pathways: (1) a content encoder that generates contextualized token representations using a long-document transformer (e.g., LongT5), and (2) a structure inducer that dynamically predicts hierarchical segmentation by clustering semantically coherent spans into latent sections and subsections using a neural stack-based parser inspired by transition systems in syntactic parsing. These latent segments form adaptive semantic units, replacing rigid structural annotations. During contrastive learning, positive pairs are sampled from within the same predicted segment or from corresponding levels in similar latent trees across documents, while negatives are drawn from跨-segment or跨-level positions. To prevent semantic diffusion across boundaries, we introduce a Boundary-Aware Contrastive Loss (BACL) that modulates the similarity scores based on the probability of crossing a latent structural boundary—penalizing high similarity between elements separated by strong segmentation signals. Additionally, we design a Structure-Regularized Augmentation strategy: instead of random masking, we mask entire predicted segments with probabilities proportional to their depth and confidence, preserving unit integrity. A key innovation is the Coherence Consistency Objective (CCO), which enforces that representations of tokens within a predicted segment remain closer in embedding space than those across boundaries, even under augmentation. This creates an intrinsic regularization against semantic drift as document length increases. LHCL enables the model to scale robustly to arbitrarily long documents by adaptively chunking them into meaningful, task-informed units without dependency on ground-truth structure. We evaluate LHCL on zero-shot retrieval, abstractive summarization, and scientific claim verification tasks using datasets like arXiv, PubMed Central, and GovReport. We hypothesize that LHCL will outperform both structure-agnostic baselines (SimCSE, ConSERT) and structure-dependent methods (HSA, LA(SER)³), particularly in low-annotation or cross-domain settings, demonstrating superior generalization and reduced length sensitivity.",
